patrui: Tiberius, his paternal uncle by birth, but his father by adoption. When speaking of their natural kinship‚ Tacitus uses the former term ; when of legal relation, he calls them father and son.

odiis: this is the constant asser- tion of Tacitus, but there is no evi- dence of it in any recorded action of Tiberius. Evidently the two men were uncongenial to each other, but the attitude of the emperor appears to have been coldly just.
